# JMeter Script Guardrails

## Core Principle

Think and act like a performance test engineer. Follow the same diagnostic workflow
a human engineer would: run a smoke test, find the first failure, diagnose it with
real data, apply a targeted fix, re-test, and repeat.

## Smoke Test Configuration

- Smoke tests MUST use exactly: **1 thread, 1 second ramp-up, 1 loop**
- No exceptions. This is a validation run, not a load test.
- Never run a load/stress test to confirm a script edit works
- If the Thread Group has higher values, temporarily override to 1/1/1 before running

## Analyze Before Edit

- Always call `analyze_jmeter_script` before any add/edit operation
- Use the analysis output to get current `node_id` values
- Do not guess node IDs or component structure

## Dry Run First

- Always use `dry_run=true` first on add/edit operations to preview changes
- Review the dry run output before applying
- Repeat with `dry_run=false` only after confirming the preview is correct

## Re-Analyze After Edits

- After applying any edit, re-analyze the script to verify structure
- Confirm the change took effect as expected

## set_prop Property Naming by Component Type

When using `set_prop` in `edit_jmeter_component`, the correct property name format
depends on the component type:

- **Standard components** (`HTTPSamplerProxy`, `ThreadGroup`, etc.) use the
  `ClassName.propertyName` prefix format â€” e.g. `HTTPSampler.method`, `ThreadGroup.num_threads`
- **TestBean components** (`KeystoreConfig`, `JDBCSampler`, `JSR223Sampler`, etc.) use
  the **short name without any prefix** â€” e.g. `clientCertAliasVarName`, `startIndex`, `endIndex`

To identify the correct names, inspect the scaffolded properties added by
`add_jmeter_component` (via `analyze_jmeter_script` or reading the JMX directly) and
match exactly. Using the wrong prefix on a TestBean will silently create a duplicate
property that JMeter ignores, leaving the original value unchanged.

## One Fix at a Time

- During debugging, fix only the first failing sampler
- Re-test after each fix before moving to the next issue
- Do not batch-fix multiple samplers blind

## Backup Protection

- The HITL tools create automatic backups on every non-dry-run mutation
- Backups are stored in `artifacts/{test_run_id}/jmeter/backups/`
- Never delete backups

## Debug Iteration Limit

- Maximum 5 debug iterations per debugging session
- If the script is not clean after 5 cycles, stop and report to the user
- Provide: summary of fixes applied, remaining errors, recommendation for manual investigation

## Debug Post-Processor

- Use the built-in `jsr223_debug_postprocessor` component type for debugging
- Discover it via `list_jmeter_component_types`
- Add it via `add_jmeter_component` with `component_type="jsr223_debug_postprocessor"`
- Never create custom JSR223 PostProcessor debug scripts from scratch
- After debugging is complete, **disable** (do not delete) debug post-processors
- Set `VERBOSE_LOGGING` back to `false`

## Log Source Mapping

- `log_source="jmeter"` for local smoke tests
- `log_source="blazemeter"` for BlazeMeter cloud tests

## User Consent

- Never start a debugging workflow unless the user explicitly requests it
- Close JMeter GUI during HITL edits â€” advise the user before starting

## Stop on Environment Issues

Stop debugging immediately and report to the user if:
- HTTP 401/403 on login/auth samplers (credential or permission failure)
- HTTP 5xx on all or most samplers (environment down or deployment in progress)
- Connection refused/timeout on all samplers (environment unreachable)
- Repeated identical errors across all samplers (systemic issue, not script bug)
